            Rwanda accepts deportees
          </h2>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-image
          border-radius="10px"
          padding="10px 12px"
          width="600px"
          src="https://www.geopoliticalsummary.com/email/images/rwanda-us-migrant-deal-trump.jpg"
          alt="Former US President Donald Trump holds a photo while seated at the Oval Office desk, surrounded by officials including representatives from Rwanda, illustrating the agreement for Rwanda to receive migrants from the US."
          href="https://www.geopoliticalsummary.com"
        />
        <mj-text padding="0px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#A9A7AF">
          <p style="font-size: 12px; line-height: 1.2; color: #a9a7af">
            <i>
              The White House did not comment on the agreement yet, but said it
              is speaking with countries willing to help deport migrants who
              entered under former President Biden. Source: Reuters via Sky
              News</i
            >
          </p>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">
            <strong>The what:</strong> Rwanda has agreed to take
            <a
              style="
                text-decoration: none;
                border-bottom: 2px solid #06266d;
                color: black;
              "
              href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-7-aug-25-spotlight-h1-1-up-to-250-migrants?source=website"
              target="_blank"
              >up to 250 migrants</a
            >
            from the US under an agreement with President Trump. Under the
            scheme, Rwanda will approve each individual for resettlement, and
            the migrants will receive workforce training, healthcare, and
            accommodation. An unspecified US grant is expected to support the
            program.
          </p>
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">
            <strong>The background:</strong> The Trump administration has
            approached several African countries to accept deportees whose
            homelands refused to take them. Eswatini and South Sudan have
            accepted some deportees, including those with a criminal record.
            Rwanda, which has experience with evacuating
            <a
              style="
                text-decoration: none;
                border-bottom: 2px solid #06266d;
                color: black;
              "
              href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-7-aug-25-spotlight-h1-2-refugees-from-libya?source=website"
              target="_blank"
              >refugees from Libya</a
            >, sees the program as aligned with its values on reintegration and
            rehabilitation.
          </p>
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">
            <strong>The criticism:</strong> Human rights groups question the
            legality of sending migrants to a third country (a nation that is
            not a migrant's place of origin) and Rwandaâ€™s poor human rights
            record. Rwandaâ€™s
            <a
              style="
                text-decoration: none;
                border-bottom: 2px solid #06266d;
                color: black;
              "
              href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-7-aug-25-spotlight-h1-3-role-in-the-conflict?source=website"
              target="_blank"
              >role in the conflict</a
            >
            in the Democratic Republic of Congo also raises concerns about its
            credibility for facilitating these migrants.
          </p>
        </mj-text>
