          </h2>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size: 18px; line-height: 1.5">
            <strong>
              Summary: Trump will hold trilateral talks with Armenia and
              Azerbaijan to discuss a potential peace framework.
            </strong>
          </p>
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">
            <strong>The what:</strong> Armenian PM Nikol Pashinyan
            <a
              style="
                text-decoration: none;
                border-bottom: 2px solid #06266d;
                color: black;
              "
              href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-7-aug-25-spotlight-h2-4-will-meet-president-trump?source=website"
              target="_blank"
              >will meet President Trump</a
            >
            and Azerbaijani President Ilham Aliyev in Washington. The trilateral
            talks aim to boost economic cooperation, enhance stability, and
            potentially announce a peace framework. This meeting follows the
            <a
              style="
                text-decoration: none;
                border-bottom: 2px solid #06266d;
                color: black;
              "
              href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-7-aug-25-spotlight-h2-5-abu-dhabi-summit?source=website"
              target="_blank"
              >Abu Dhabi summit</a
            >
            in July, where both sides agreed to continue bilateral negotiations.
          </p>
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">
            <strong>The roots:</strong> The conflict started when
            Nagorno-Karabakh broke away from Azerbaijan in the late 1980s,
            causing decades of tension. Azerbaijan regained control of the
            territory in 2023, forcing nearly 100,000 Armenians to flee. Armenia
            accuses Baku of ethnic cleansing, while Azerbaijan insists it is
            ensuring safety and that it has not forced ethnic Armenians to flee
            the Karabakh region (<a
              style="
                text-decoration: none;
                border-bottom: 2px solid #06266d;
                color: black;
              "
              href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-7-aug-25-spotlight-h2-6-the-explainer?source=website"
              target="_blank"
              >the explainer</a
            >).
          </p>
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5; filter: blur(5px)">
            <strong>The big picture:</strong> The Washington summit is part of a
            larger US strategy to reduce Russian and Iranian influence in the
            South Caucasus. Critics say that the US may focus on its strategic
            interests in the region, such as gaining control over the
            <a
              style="
                text-decoration: none;
                border-bottom: 2px solid #06266d;
                color: black;
              "
              href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-7-aug-25-spotlight-h2-7-zangezeur-corridor?source=website"
              target="_blank"
              >Zangezeur corridor</a
            >
            (a 43 km land route linking Azerbaijan to its exclave of Nakhchivan
            via southern Armenia). US control over this key route would threaten
            Russia and Iranâ€™s control of the regional trade flows.
          </p>
